const P = {
thename:{name:"„Gott dank“ · the name itself",conf:"verified",years:"1700s → today",place:"Hanau → Galicia → the world",rel:"Origin of the surname",facts:{Meaning:"'Thank God', German & Yiddish",Family:"The name passed through a WOMAN, Gittel's husband took HER surname at marriage",Shtetl:"Isterik (Yiddish) = Ustrzyki Dolne, SE Galicia, the documented origin town of the Vaytman-Gottdank / Israel line",Decree:"1787, Emperor Joseph II required all Galician Jews to adopt fixed German surnames by January 1788",Earliest:"A 'Hanau (Gottdank)' family in 1700s Germany, but that cluster traces to Lorraine, so its link to the Galician Gottdanks is unproven"},story:["Gittel was a midwife, 'like her female ancestors.' Her husband Kalman took her last name when they married, and their children carried it out of Galicia to New York. So every Gottdank in this tree carries a woman's name.","In 1787, Emperor Joseph II ordered all Jews in Galicia to take fixed German surnames. Families could choose a name or have one assigned. 'Gottdank', two German words meaning 'thank God', is the sort of name a family might pick when the choice was theirs. Whether ours did the choosing, nobody recorded it.","Their town was Isterik, the Yiddish name for Ustrzyki Dolne, in the far southeastern corner of old Galicia. Jews had lived there since at least the 17th century, and a census in 1765 counted 162 of them. By 1900 they were 61 percent of the population. In Isterik, Abraham Vaytman took the name from his wife Miriam, and Kalman took it from Gittel the same way. The Jewish community there was killed or deported to Belzec in the war. A 'Hanau Gottdank' family shows up in 1700s Germany too, but that cluster traces to Lorraine, so whether it connects to the Galician line is anyone's guess."],src:["Family document: 'Gottdank Descendants'","JewishGen Lesko Yizkor (Isterik = Ustrzyki Dolne)","Virtual Shtetl (sztetl.org.pl): Ustrzyki Dolne community history","Habsburg Edict on Jewish Names, July 23, 1787","Forebears (surname distribution)","Geni (Hanau & Vaytman-Gottdank)"]},
gittel:{name:"Gittel Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"19th c.",place:"Galicia (the Isterik region)",rel:"Generation One · the matriarch whose name the family carries",facts:{Trade:"Midwife, 'like her female ancestors'",Husband:"Kalman ('Coleman')",Surname:"On her son Charles's 1909 marriage record she is 'Gitte Bernfeld', so her maiden name may be Bernfeld (Berenfeld)",America:"Never emigrated",Rest:"Said to be buried in Pápa, Hungary, but no record confirms it; treat as family memory"},story:["Gittel delivered babies in Galicia, the way her mother and grandmother had. The story in the family is that Gottdank was hers, and that Kalman took it when they married. Her children carried it out of the shtetl, to Chicago and New York.","She never crossed the ocean. Her son Charles's 1909 New York marriage record names her 'Gitte Bernfeld,' which leaves open whether the Gottdank name came down through her birth family or reached her some other way.","Maryem Gottdank, a midwife of Isterik, was killed when the town's Jews were sent to Bełżec in 1942. Her granddaughter, the Yiddish scholar Miriam Gottdank Isaacs, drew her from memory. Whether Maryem was Gittel's daughter, her cousin, or simply another woman with the same rare name and trade in the same small town is the one question the records haven't closed."],gap:"A 1909 record names her 'Gitte Bernfeld,' so her maiden name may be Bernfeld (Berenfeld), and which spouse was born 'Gottdank' is contested. The Pápa burial stays unverified; the midwife Maryem Gottdank of Isterik is the best lead to her European life.",src:["Family document, Generation 1","NYC marriage record, 1909 (son Charles, mother 'Gitte Bernfeld')","JewishGen Lesko Yizkor (Isterik)","Jewish Women's Archive, Maryem Gottdank, midwife of Isterik","Bełżec deportation list (Sanok district, Sept 1942)"]},
coleman:{name:"Kalman ('Coleman') Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"d. before 1900",place:"Galicia (Isterik)",rel:"Generation One · Charles's father",facts:{Name:"Confirmed as 'Kalman Gottdank' on his son Charles's 1909 marriage record",Etymology:"Kalman is the Yiddish form of Kalonymos (Ancient Greek: 'beautiful name'), an Ashkenazic name traced to the medieval Rhineland; its recorded American equivalent is Coleman",Died:"Before Bernhard & Bertha's 1900 wedding",Surname:"On the record he carries the Gottdank name; family lore says he took it from Gittel at marriage",Shtetl:"By the 1880s Jews were the majority in Isterik (Ustrzyki Dolne); a railway reached the town in 1872"},story:["Gittel's husband, dead before the century turned. His son Charles's 1909 marriage record names him Kalman Gottdank. Kalman is the Yiddish form of Kalonymos, a name carried in Ashkenazic communities since the medieval Rhineland; its American twin is Coleman.","The Isterik of his generation was growing. A railway reached the town in 1872, connecting it to Przemyśl and Sanok, and by the 1880s Jews were the majority of the population, merchants the biggest group among them. His children went to New York and Chicago; he didn't make it that far.","Kalman becomes Coleman, and generations later the family named a boy Cole. Nobody planned that, but the first ancestor's name still found its way down."],src:["Family document, Generation 1","NYC marriage record, 1909 (son Charles, father 'Kalman Gottdank')","Virtual Shtetl (sztetl.org.pl): Ustrzyki Dolne community history","Geneanet / Behind the Name (Kalman · Kalonymos · Coleman)"]},
charles:{name:"Charles Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"late 1800s – 1957",place:"Galicia → Brooklyn, NY",rel:"Gittel & Coleman's son · the New York barber",facts:{Trade:"Barber, New York",Parents:"Kalman Gottdank & Gitte Bernfeld, the 'Coleman & Gittel' of family memory, Generation One",Married:"Fanny Krantz, in Manhattan, 1909",Immigrated:"From Galicia via Ellis Island; naturalized in New York, 1912",Children:"Lillian · Helen · Jerry (Jerome) · MILTON",Census:"Brooklyn in the 1940 census, with Fannie and Milton",Died:"September 25, 1957, buried Flushing, Queens"},story:["He landed in New York from Galicia, married Fanny Krantz in Manhattan in 1909, and cut hair for a living. Barbering was a common trade for Galician Jews, and immigrant barbers in New York were quick to organize their own unions.","Charles and Fannie had four children: Lillian, Helen, Jerry, and Milton. Jerry was born in 1911; Milton, the youngest, in 1921. By 1940 Charles, Fannie, and Milton were living in Brooklyn, and the other three were out on their own. He had been naturalized in 1912, early enough to feel like a citizen by the time his family was complete.","He died September 25, 1957, and was buried in Flushing, Queens. His parents were Kalman Gottdank and Gitte Bernfeld, the Coleman and Gittel of family memory, and he carried their name across the ocean."],src:["Family document, Generations 2–3","NYC marriage record, 1909 (parents Kalman Gottdank & Gitte Bernfeld; wife Fanny Krantz)","1940 US Census, Brooklyn","New York naturalization, 1912","Find A Grave (Charles Gottdank, d. 1957, Flushing, Queens)","Wikipedia, Galician Jews (over 65% of barbers in Galicia were Jewish)","jewishcurrents.org, 'A Short History of Jews in the American Labor Movement' (Jewish barbers organized their own unions in New York)"]},
fannieK:{name:"Fannie (Krantz) Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1894 – 1972",place:"Bronx, NY",rel:"Charles's wife · Generation Two",facts:{Parents:"Jacob Krantz ⚭ Martha Feit",Married:"Charles, in Manhattan, 1909",Match:"SSDI 'Fanny Gottdank, b. Apr 20 1894, d. 1972'; buried at New Montefiore Cemetery, West Babylon",Children:"Lillian · Helen · Jerry · Milton"},story:["Fannie Krantz married Charles Gottdank in a Manhattan ceremony in 1909. She was from the Bronx, the daughter of Jacob Krantz and Martha Feit. Together she and Charles raised four children: Lillian, Helen, Jerry, and Milton. Jerry was born in 1911; Milton, the youngest, arrived ten years later.","By 1940 she and Charles were still in Brooklyn with Milton, the others out on their own by then. Charles died in September 1957; Fannie lived another fifteen years after that. She died in 1972 and rests at New Montefiore Cemetery in West Babylon, the large Jewish cemetery on Long Island that first opened in 1928. Two of her grandchildren, Lynn Jay and Kurt, lie there as well, in Phyllis's family plot."],gap:"A different Fannie Gottdank turns up in the records (d. 1967, Flushing), not her. Hers is the New Montefiore grave, 1894–1972.",src:["Family document","SSDI (Fanny, 1894-1972)","Find A Grave Index (New Montefiore Cemetery, West Babylon)","Wikipedia, New Montefiore Cemetery (founded 1928)"]},
lillian:{name:"Lillian (Gottdank) Johnson",conf:"verified",years:"20th c.",place:"New York · Bronx",rel:"Charles & Fannie's daughter · Milton's sister",facts:{FirstHusband:"Morris Birnbaum",Children:"Ira · June",Son:"Ira Birnbaum: De Witt Clinton HS (Bronx), Lehigh Univ. (entered age 16), Merchant Marine South Pacific WWII, GM UA Columbia Cablevision 1976 (Westchester County), d. age 94; wife Marilyn 71 yrs, sons Jesse & Eric"},story:["Lillian Gottdank married Morris Birnbaum and had two children with him, a son Ira and a daughter June. Ira went to De Witt Clinton High School in the Bronx, which puts the family in a different borough from Charles's Brooklyn. She later married again and went by Johnson.","Ira got into Lehigh University at sixteen, left to serve with the Merchant Marine in the South Pacific during World War II, and graduated from Lehigh after his service. He became general manager of UA Columbia Cablevision in 1976 and is credited with bringing cable television to Westchester County. He died at ninety-four, leaving his wife Marilyn and their sons Jesse and Eric."],src:["Family document, Generation 4","Ira Birnbaum obituary, New York Times / Legacy.com, Jan 2022 (De Witt Clinton HS; Lehigh Univ., entered age 16; Merchant Marine South Pacific WWII; GM UA Columbia Cablevision 1976, Westchester; wife Marilyn 71 years, sons Jesse and Eric; d. age 94)"]},
helenS:{name:"Helen (Gottdank) Stober",conf:"verified",years:"20th c.",place:"New York",rel:"Charles & Fannie's daughter · Milton's sister",facts:{Husband:"Leo Stober",Children:"Judy Wahrman (née Stober) · Marvin Stober",Note:"'We were very friendly with Helen and her husband Leo', the document",JudysHusband:"Ralph Wahrman (1939-2011), NYC native; Stuyvesant HS · Queens College BA · Michigan State PhD; sociology professor at BGSU for 34 years; edited Sociological Focus (journal of NCSA) from 1988; d. Sept 30 2011; children Francine · Eric · Anna",Marvin:"Special Education lecturer, City College of New York (CUNY)"},story:["Helen, Charles and Fannie's daughter, married Leo Stober. 'We were very friendly with Helen and her husband Leo' is how the family remembered them.","Their daughter Judy married Ralph Wahrman, a New York City native who had graduated from Stuyvesant High School and Queens College before earning his sociology PhD at Michigan State. He spent 34 years on the faculty at Bowling Green State University in Ohio and became editor of Sociological Focus, the journal of the North Central Sociological Association, in 1988. Ralph died in September 2011; he and Judy had three children, Francine, Eric, and Anna.","Her son Marvin has taught special education at City College of New York, part of CUNY."],src:["Family document, Generations 3–4","Sentinel-Tribune (Bowling Green, OH), 1 Oct 2011: Ralph Wahrman obituary (wife Judith Stober; NYC native; Stuyvesant HS; Queens College; Michigan State PhD; BGSU 34 years; d. 30 Sept 2011, age 71)","BGSU Retirees newsletter, Nov 2011 (Ralph Wahrman, emeritus prof. of sociology)","ASA Footnotes, Sept/Oct 2013 (Wahrman became editor of Sociological Focus in 1988)","CUNY Academic Commons / Rate My Professors (Marvin Stober, Education, City College of New York)"]},
jerry:{name:"Jerry (Jerome) Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1911 – 1993",place:"New York → Miami Beach, FL",rel:"Charles & Fannie's son · Milton's brother",facts:{Wife:"Molly (1910–2011)",Children:"Frank · Alan · Linda",Match:"SSDI: Jerome Gottdank, b. Oct 19 1911, d. Dec 22 1993, Miami Beach"},story:["Jerry went by Jerome on paper. He was born October 19, 1911, married Molly, and they raised three kids: Frank, Alan, and Linda. The family settled in Spring Valley, a Rockland County town that filled with New York Jews after the war. Alan went to Brooklyn College, class of 1960.","Jerome retired to Miami Beach and died there on December 22, 1993. Molly outlived him by years. She was born March 31, 1910, and died in Spring Valley on April 21, 2011, at a hundred and one."],src:["AncientFaces Gottdank surname records (ancientfaces.com/surname/gottdank-family-history/14053)","Brooklyn College In Memoriam (brooklyn.edu/alumni/in-memoriam-13-1)","SSDI: Jerome Gottdank, b. Oct 19 1911, d. Dec 22 1993, Miami Beach","Encyclopedia.com, 'Rockland County' (postwar Jewish families from NYC relocated to Spring Valley and Rockland County)"]},
mollyR:{name:"Molly Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1910 – 2011",place:"Brooklyn → Spring Valley, NY",rel:"Jerry's wife · mother of Frank, Alan & Linda",facts:{Born:"March 31, 1910",Died:"April 21, 2011, aged 101",Children:"Frank(lin) · Alan · Linda"},story:["Molly was born on March 31, 1910, in Brooklyn. She married Jerry and together they moved to Spring Valley, where they raised Frank, Alan, and Linda.","Jerry retired to Miami Beach and died there in December 1993. Molly stayed on in Spring Valley. She died there on April 21, 2011, at a hundred and one."],src:["Family document","SSDI","Radaris relative listings (confirmed)"]},
franklin:{name:"Franklin D. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"b. ~1955",place:"Spring Valley, NY → Lewes, DE",rel:"Son of Jerry & Molly",facts:{Wife:"Wendy",Parents:"Jerry ⚭ Molly, per the family document ('Frank')",Lived:"Spring Valley & Monsey, NY; Selbyville area, DE; now Lewes, DE",Home:"Mariners' Retreat, Lewes; built and moved in March 2020; outdoor shower off primary bath via glass door"},story:["Franklin, 'Frank' in the family, is Jerry and Molly's son, which makes him Brian and Dale's first cousin. He grew up in Spring Valley, the Rockland County town his parents had settled, and stayed up that way through Monsey before heading south.","Before they settled in Lewes, he and Wendy had a home in the Selbyville area, the flat stretch of southern Delaware close to the Maryland line. When they decided to build, they chose Mariners' Retreat in Lewes. The house they designed has an outdoor shower off the primary bath, reached through a glass door. They moved in March 2020, right as the world shut down. From fifty degrees and up, rain or not, they take it outside. They keep flower boxes and bird feeders and walk to the farmers market in old Lewes."],src:["Family document (son 'Frank')","Delaware Beach Life, 'Getting Outdoors' cottage tour: Wendy & Frank Gottdank, Mariners' Retreat, Lewes; prior Selbyville-area home; outdoor shower via glass door off primary bath; shower from 50 degrees up; moved March 2020","Radaris (b. ~1955; Molly relative listing; prior addresses 230 Kearsing Pkwy Monsey NY & 21 David Dr Spring Valley NY)","LocateFamily (household with Wendy)"]},
wendy:{name:"Wendy Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Spring Valley, NY → Selbyville, DE → Lewes, DE",rel:"Wife of Franklin",facts:{Household:"21 David Drive, Spring Valley NY (with Franklin); then Selbyville area, DE; now Mariners' Retreat, Lewes DE",MistAway:"MistAway mosquito misting system at the Selbyville home by at least 2015",OutdoorShower:"Her design idea for the Lewes build: glass door inside the indoor shower opens directly to an open-air outdoor shower with no roof; used from 50 degrees up, rain or not"},story:["She and Franklin had a home in the Selbyville area first, the flat stretch of southern Delaware close to the Maryland line. They had a MistAway mosquito misting system out there by at least 2015.","When they built at Mariners' Retreat in Lewes, Wendy's piece of the design was the outdoor shower. She wanted it connected directly to the house, so the answer was a glass door inside the indoor shower that opens straight outside. From fifty degrees up, rain or not, that's where they go, and since there's no roof they get the sun in the afternoon and the stars at night. They moved in March 2020, right as everything locked down, and from there they walk to old Lewes and the Saturday farmers market."],src:["Delaware Beach Life, 'Getting Outdoors' cottage tour: Wendy & Frank Gottdank, Mariners' Retreat Lewes; Wendy's design: glass door in indoor shower opens to outdoor shower (no roof); 50 degrees and up; moved March 2020; prior Selbyville-area home; walk to Lewes and farmers market","Lawns Unlimited (lawnsunlimited.com/wendy-gottdank/): Wendy review, 'The MistAway system really works! We had hardly any insects bother us last summer. Just signed up again for 2016'","Radaris address pairing: 21 David Drive Spring Valley NY + Lewes DE"]},
allan:{name:"Allan M. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"~1939 – 2025",place:"Brooklyn → Spring Valley, NY → Manhattan UWS",rel:"Son of Jerry & Molly",facts:{Parents:"Jerry ⚭ Molly, the document's 'Alan'",Education:"Brooklyn College, Class of 1960",Home:"161 W 61st St (The Alfred), Lincoln Center, Manhattan",Died:"~March 2025, Ridgewood Chapels, NY",Siblings:"Frank(lin) · Linda"},story:["Brooklyn College put him down as Allan M. Gottdank, Class of 1960, though in the family he was always Alan. He was one of Jerry and Molly's three, raised in Spring Valley after the family moved up from Brooklyn, one of the Rockland County towns New York Jewish families came to after the war.","He made it to Manhattan after college and settled at 161 West 61st Street, The Alfred, a tower that went up beside Lincoln Center in 1987. He stayed on the Upper West Side for decades, and when he died in 2025, Morton-Ridgewood at Ridgewood Chapels handled the arrangements. His brother Franklin and his sister Linda outlived him."],src:["Brooklyn College In Memoriam (lists 'Allan M. Gottdank '60', deaths reported Apr-Nov 2025): brooklyn.edu/alumni/in-memoriam-13-1/","locatefamily.com (Allan M. Gottdank, 161 W 61st St, NY, captured 2019)","mortonridgewood.com (Ridgewood Chapels, Queens)","cityrealty.com (The Alfred, 161 W 61st: 38-story condo opened 1987, Lincoln Center district, designed Jung/Brannen Associates)","jerry/mollyR tree entries (family settled Spring Valley after the war; Franklin entry confirms Spring Valley upbringing)","Encyclopedia.com, Rockland County (postwar Jewish families from NYC to Spring Valley, cited in jerry entry)"]},
lindaJ:{name:"Linda Gottdank",conf:"likely",years:"living",place:"Spring Valley, NY",rel:"Daughter of Jerry & Molly",facts:{Parents:"Jerry (Jerome) ⚭ Molly",Siblings:"Frank(lin) · the late Alan"},story:["Jerry and Molly raised three children in Spring Valley: Frank, Alan, and Linda. They'd moved up from Brooklyn after the war, part of the wave of New York Jewish families buying houses in Rockland County through the 1950s and 1960s. She outlived her brother Alan, who died in 2025."],gap:"No independently matched record yet.",src:["Family document, Generation 4 (lists Frank, Alan, and Linda as Jerry & Molly's children)","Encyclopedia.com, 'Rockland County' (postwar Jewish families from NYC to Spring Valley; also cited in jerry entry)","allan entry (Brooklyn College In Memoriam, 2025; 'His brother Franklin and his sister Linda outlived him')"]},
milton:{name:"Milton Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1921 – 1984",place:"Coney Island, Brooklyn, NY",rel:"Charles & Fannie's youngest son",facts:{Born:"February 28, 1921, New York",Parents:"Charles (the barber) ⚭ Fannie Krantz",Siblings:"Lillian · Helen (Stober) · Jerry",Census:"Still in the Brooklyn household with Charles and Fannie in 1940, the last of the four at home",Home:"West 5th Street, Coney Island, Brooklyn",Wife:"Phyllis Schraeter",Children:"Dale · Brian · Lynn Jay & Kurt (lost as toddlers)",Died:"August 1, 1984"},story:["He was nineteen and still at home with Charles and Fannie in 1940, the last of their four in the house while Lillian, Helen, and Jerry were out on their own. When he married Phyllis Schraeter, they settled on West 5th Street in Coney Island, near the boardwalk, in the neighborhood that had been Jewish since the 1910s.","They had four children and lost two of them young. Lynn Jay died in May 1953, not yet three. Kurt died in June 1961 at two. Both are buried in the Mandel Family Circle at New Montefiore, Phyllis's family's plot. Dale grew up in that apartment by the ocean. Brian likely did too, before they went their own ways.","Milton died on August 1, 1984. He was sixty-three."],src:["Family document, Generations 3–4","1940 US Census, Brooklyn","SSDI (1921–1984, NY)","LocateFamily (West 5th Street household record)","My Jewish Learning, 'Jews in Coney Island: A History' (Jewish families in Coney Island since the 1910s)","Find A Grave, Lynn Jay Gottdank (memorial 151784528); Kurt Gottdank (memorial 151738023)"]},
phyllis:{name:"Phyllis (Schraeter) Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"c. 1922 – 2012",place:"Brooklyn, NY",rel:"Milton's wife",facts:{Maiden:"SCHRAETER, the 'S' in her directory listing",Parents:"Jacob Schraeter ⚭ Bertha Blazer",School:"Her mother, Bertha Blazer Schraeter, co-founded the Shulamith School for Girls at 4910 14th Ave, Borough Park, in 1930, with Nacha Rivkin and Rabbi M.G. Volk; the first Orthodox Jewish elementary school for girls in North America",Grandparents:"Aaron Schraeter ⚭ Sara Guttman · Wolf Blazer ⚭ Hannah Mandel",Deeper:"David Schraeter · Feivush Gutman ⚭ Hannah Leah · Hersh Mandel ⚭ Ida",Died:"Oct 19, 2012, aged 90",Rest:"New Montefiore, the Mandel Family Circle plot, near her two children"},story:["Phyllis was a Schraeter before she married Milton, and her family runs back three more generations of Galician Jews: Schraeter, Blazer, Guttman, Mandel. Her mother, Bertha Blazer Schraeter, co-founded the Shulamith School for Girls in 1930, opening at 4910 14th Avenue in Borough Park with Nacha Rivkin and Rabbi M.G. Volk. It was the first Orthodox Jewish elementary school for girls in North America.","Phyllis raised four children in the apartment by the Coney Island boardwalk and buried two of them young. She outlived Milton by almost thirty years and died in 2012, at ninety. She lies in her own family's plot at New Montefiore, the Mandel Family Circle, near the two children she lost."],src:["Family document","Wikipedia, Shulamith School for Girls (founded 1930, Borough Park, Brooklyn)","New Montefiore Cemetery (Phyllis, Mandel Family Circle)"]},
lostKids:{name:"Lynn Jay & Kurt, lost young",conf:"likely",years:"d. 1953 & 1961, as toddlers",place:"New Montefiore Cemetery, West Babylon, NY",rel:"Children of Milton & Phyllis · Brian and Dale's siblings",facts:{Lynn:"Lynn Jay Gottdank, b. Oct 9, 1950, d. May 31, 1953; her stone reads simply 'DAUGHTER'",Kurt:"Kurt Gottdank, b. 1959, d. June 5, 1961 (age 2), marked 'Child'",Plot:"Both in Section 4, Block 11 at New Montefiore, the Mandel Family Circle, the burial society of Phyllis's mother's family (the Mandels)"},story:["For years the family knew Milton and Phyllis had lost two children, and now they have names. Lynn Jay died in 1953, not yet three; her stone reads only 'DAUGHTER.' Kurt died in 1961, just turned two. They lie together in Section 4, Block 11 at New Montefiore Cemetery in West Babylon.","What ties them to Milton and Phyllis is the ground itself. The plot belongs to the Mandel Family Circle, the burial society of Phyllis's mother's family. Two Gottdank toddlers of the right years, resting in Phyllis's own family's plot. Short of a record naming their parents, it's about as sure as it gets."],gap:"As close to proven as it gets short of a record naming the parents: two Gottdank children of the right years, in Phyllis's family's own (Mandel) burial plot.",src:["Find A Grave, Lynn Jay Gottdank (memorial 151784528)","Find A Grave, Kurt Gottdank (memorial 151738023), New Montefiore Cemetery"]},
brian:{name:"Brian R. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Downingtown, PA",rel:"Son of Milton & Phyllis",facts:{Household:"Santillo Way, Downingtown, same record as Cole",With:"Laurie Gottdank, same address & phone"},story:["Brian lives on Santillo Way in Downingtown, the same household where Cole shows up, on the same phone line.","He grew up, we think, in Milton and Phyllis's Brooklyn house, and carried the name to Chester County. Almost one in five American Gottdanks lives in Pennsylvania, and that's basically Brian's household."],src:["Laurie Gottdank LinkedIn (linkedin.com/in/lauriegottdank)","Labcorp IR: completed Chiltern acquisition Sept 1, 2017","Household record: Santillo Way, Downingtown, since 2001"]},
laurie:{name:"Laurie Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Downingtown, PA",rel:"Wife of Brian (household record)",facts:{Household:"Same Santillo Way address & phone as Brian and Cole",Listed:"Since 2001"},story:["Laurie runs HR systems, the back-end software that keeps payroll, benefits, and org charts straight for big companies. When Labcorp bought the clinical research firm Chiltern in 2017, somebody had to move thousands of Chiltern employees across forty-some countries onto Labcorp's systems without a single paycheck going wrong. Laurie was on that team. She started at Chiltern's office in King of Prussia, a short drive east of home, and stayed on at Labcorp Drug Development after the deal closed.","She studied at Pace University's Lubin School of Business and holds the PHR credential through SHRM. The family has been at the Santillo Way address in Downingtown, in the Chester County exurbs west of Philadelphia, since 2001. She volunteered with the Downingtown Area School District, the district her kids went through, and put in time at All4paws Animal Rescue.","Lately she's in Johns Island, South Carolina, the big Lowcountry sea island outside Charleston. The kids are grown and gone, and she and Brian moved south."],src:["LocateFamily (Downingtown household, 2001–2024)"]},
cole:{name:"Cole Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"b. ~1997",place:"Downingtown, PA → San Francisco, CA",rel:"Son of Brian & Laurie",facts:{Household:"Raised at the Santillo Way house, Downingtown",Now:"San Francisco, CA"},story:["Cole grew up in the house on Santillo Way in Downingtown, in Chester County, Pennsylvania, and started building things on a computer young. He studied at West Chester University, the state school about fifteen minutes south of where he grew up. From there he went to San Francisco.","He co-founded Helicone, a tool that did observability for AI apps, the kind of logging and debugging teams need behind their API calls. The company went through Y Combinator, which put him near the front of the wave of AI tooling that followed ChatGPT. He started on the engineering side and later moved into go-to-market. In 2026 Mintlify acquired Helicone, and Cole came along with it.","On the side he built DebateAI, an AI debate platform, along with a handful of smaller projects. Away from the keyboard he cooks, picking up techniques from Kenji Lopez-Alt, and he plays basketball when he can."],src:["colegottdank.com (portfolio)","linkedin.com/in/colegottdank","helicone.ai/blog/joining-mintlify","mintlify.com/blog/mintlify-acquires-helicone","foundertrace.com/companies/helicone_yc_w23","rocketreach.co/cole-gottdank"]},
annalyn:{name:"Annalyn Gottdank",conf:"likely",years:"living",place:"Downingtown, PA",rel:"Daughter of Brian & Laurie",facts:{Work:"Wawa, Inc.",Engaged:"Kyle Graefe (Zola registry)"},story:["Annalyn works at Wawa, the Pennsylvania convenience-store chain that's a fixture around Downingtown, the Chester County town where she lives.","She's engaged to Kyle Graefe, with a registry up on Zola. The Gottdank name is vanishingly rare, so a Gottdank in this small Chester County borough is almost certainly one of ours, and the records make it plain: she's Brian and Laurie's daughter, and Bridget's sister."],gap:"Not yet tied to the household record by address.",src:["Zola registry (annalynandkyle): wedding date May 29, 2022","LinkedIn: Customer Service Associate, Wawa, Downingtown PA","Public people-records: parents Brian R & Laurie A (Cassidy) Gottdank; sister Bridget R Gottdank"]},
bridget:{name:"Bridget Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Downingtown, PA → Israel",rel:"Daughter of Brian & Laurie · Cole and Annalyn's sister",facts:{Education:"West Chester University, BA, political science & public policy",Aliyah:"Moved from the U.S. to Israel in 2021",Work:"Recruitment & Marketing Manager, Yahel Israel",Studio:"Founder, Anava Creative, marketing & design"},story:["Brian and Laurie's daughter, Cole's sister. She studied political science and public policy at West Chester, the same school as Cole, then made the family's longest move yet: aliyah to Israel in 2021, after a fellowship in Haifa in 2019.","In Israel she runs recruitment and marketing for Yahel, a social-change nonprofit, and her own studio, Anava Creative. She voted in her first Israeli election in 2022. Gittel's great-great-granddaughter, casting a ballot in a country her Galician ancestors never reached."],src:["LinkedIn (Bridget Gottdank, Yahel Israel)","Anava Creative (anavacreative.co)","Yahel Israel team bios","JTA / Times of Israel, Nov 2022"]},
dale:{name:"Dale D. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Brooklyn → San Diego (1989)",rel:"Son of Milton & Phyllis (likely)",facts:{Born:"Brooklyn, NY",Education:"Princeton",Key:"Also listed at Phyllis's Brooklyn apartment",Community:"UUFSD board · Torrey Pines Gulls officer"},story:["Born in Brooklyn, Princeton-educated, in San Diego since 1989. He's on the board of the Unitarian Universalist Fellowship of San Dieguito and an officer of the Torrey Pines Gulls glider club, quoted in the local papers defending the club's cliff-soaring hours.","Dale grew up in the same West 5th Street apartment as Phyllis. He and Brian, Milton and Phyllis's sons, went separate ways, one west, one to Pennsylvania."],src:["uufsd.org","torreypinesgulls.org","La Jolla Light, Jan 7 2022","LocateFamily (Brooklyn + San Diego)"]},
nancy:{name:"Nancy Hebert",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"San Diego, CA",rel:"Wife of Dale · deep American roots",facts:{Met:"Dale, at Princeton",Career:"Healthcare finance, Scripps, Kaiser",Roots:"Cajun Louisiana (Deshotels, Guillory, Berzas) · French Canada (Desautels, Montreal 1631) · colonial New England (Ford, Hingham MA)",Deepest:"Andrew Ford, b. ~1620 England, d. 1693 Hingham, Massachusetts; Thomas Desautels, b. 1600 Malicorne, France"},story:["Nancy's roots run deep into early America. A Cajun line out of Evangeline Parish (Deshotels, Guillory, Berzas dit La Fleur), a French-Canadian line through Pierre Desautels of 1631 Montreal, and a New England line of Hezekiah Fords going back to Andrew Ford, who left England around 1620 and died in Hingham, Massachusetts in 1693.","Jordan and Jessica carry both sides at once: Galician shtetl midwives and Plymouth-era Puritans."],src:["UUFSD biography"]},
jordan:{name:"Jordan E. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"San Diego, CA",rel:"Son of Dale & Nancy · patent attorney",facts:{Profession:"Patent attorney, Partner, Knobbe Martens (San Diego)",Education:"Oberlin BA · UCLA Law JD",Career:"Joined Knobbe Martens 2015, made partner Jan 1, 2022",Work:"Patent prosecution across electronics, optics, medical devices, transportation, sporting goods"},story:["Dale and Nancy's son, raised in San Diego, who turned the family's old habit of detail into a profession. He went to Oberlin, then UCLA for law, where he co-founded the school's Intellectual Property Law Association and spent a stretch as a judicial extern in federal court working only on patent cases.","He joined Knobbe Martens in San Diego in 2015 and made partner on the first day of 2022. He writes and prosecutes patents across a grab bag of fields, electronics and optics, medical devices, transportation, even sporting goods and apparel, and the Best Lawyers guide has flagged him as one to watch. It's a long way from a Galician midwife, and it's still the same trade in a sense: getting the particulars exactly right so they hold up."],src:["Knobbe Martens professional profile (Jordan E. Gottdank, joined 2015, partner Jan 1 2022)","Knobbe Martens, 'Best Lawyers: Ones to Watch' (Patent Law, 2024-2025)","LocateFamily (Kibbings Rd household)"]},
jessica:{name:"Jessica Gottdank",conf:"likely",years:"living",place:"San Diego, CA",rel:"Daughter of Dale & Nancy (inferred)",facts:{Found:"Front Street, downtown San Diego (2017)"},story:["Jessica turns up in downtown San Diego on Front Street in 2017. Same rare surname, same city as Dale's household.","We can't tie her to the family by a shared record yet, so this part is a best guess. The likeliest read is that she's Dale and Nancy's daughter and Jordan's sister, which would put three Gottdanks in one metro. Out on her own by 2017."],gap:"Not yet tied to the Kibbings Rd household by a shared record.",src:["boldjourney.com Meet Jessica Gottdank profile (San Diego 2015, Voxy founder, introvert/music-theory self-description, LAAF, 2024 nomination)","harmony-sweepstakes.com/details/1880 (Voxy: Gottdank/Todd/Liu; 2018 LA Best Original Arrangement)","LinkedIn jessica-gottdank + ZoomInfo (Oberlin BA / Olin BS; General Atomics, Boeing, Collins Aerospace A320neo EBU; PMP)","gigsalad.com/voxy_san_diego (May 2017 review, downtown events catchment)","Current entry: Front Street, downtown San Diego, 2017"]},
bernhard:{name:"Bernhard Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"late 1800s – mid 1900s",place:"Galicia → Chicago, IL",rel:"Charles's brother · Gittel & Coleman's son",facts:{Married:"Bertha Wiesenfeld, 1900, a family from the same shtetl",Trade:"Shopkeeper, photographed before his shop",Children:"Ruth · Kate · twins Helen & Florence (died young) · Mildred",Died:"1917, about 35"},story:["Bernhard was Charles the barber's brother. He married Bertha Wiesenfeld in 1900 and ran a shop in Chicago, and one photograph survives of him standing in front of it, the only picture we have of this immigrant generation at work.","He didn't get long. He died in 1917, around thirty-five, four years after he and Bertha buried their infant twins, Helen and Florence, at the Jewish cemetery in Waldheim."],src:["Family document, Generations 2-3","AncientFaces (photo)","FindAGrave (Bernard Gottdank, 1882-1917)"]},
bertha:{name:"Bertha (Wiesenfeld) Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1878 – 1967",place:"Galicia → Chicago, IL",rel:"Wife of Bernhard · of the shtetl's other family",facts:{Born:"June 22, 1878",Married:"Bernhard, 1900",Shtetl:"Wiesenfeld traces to Kańczuga / Rzeszów in central Galicia (Aaron & Samuel Wiesenfeld founded the Kańczuger Aid Society, NYC 1902)",Died:"Oct 14, 1967, fifty years a widow"},story:["Bertha was a Wiesenfeld, from Kańczuga near Rzeszów in central Galicia, about 100 km from the Gottdanks' Isterik in the far southeast. So the old idea that the two families came from one shtetl looks wrong; they married across Galicia, not within a single town.","Her family kept a door open for the immigrants who followed: the Kańczuger Aid Society, founded in New York in 1902, with two Wiesenfelds among its directors. Bertha outlived Bernhard by fifty years. Widowed in 1917, she died in 1967."],src:["Family document","SSDI","Gesher Galicia Family Finder (Wiesenfeld, Kańczuga/Rzeszów)","Kańczuger Aid Society (1902 incorporation record)","FindAGrave (Bertha Wiesenfeld Gottdank, d. 1967)"]},
ruthM:{name:"Ruth (Gottdank) Marek",conf:"verified",years:"early 20th c.",place:"Chicago, IL",rel:"Daughter of Bernhard & Bertha",facts:{Husband:"Michael Marek, a Chicago machinist (Continental Can Co.)",Children:"Jewel (b. 1935) · twins Donald & Bernard",Home:"West Fulton Street, Chicago, from before WWII into the 1960s"},story:["Oldest of the Chicago daughters. She married Michael Marek, a machinist who spent most of his working life at the Continental Can Company, and they raised three kids in a house on West Fulton Street on the city's near West Side, from before the war into the 1960s. The children were Jewel, born in 1935, and twin boys, Donald and Bernard.","Her father Bernhard had died in 1917, when Ruth was still a girl, so she came up in Bertha's long widowhood. That Jewel arrived in 1935 puts Ruth's own marriage in the early thirties and her birth back near 1910, right at the front of the Chicago-born generation."],src:["Family document, Generation 4","AncientFaces (Michael Marek, Chicago machinist, Continental Can Co.; wife Ruth Gottdank; children Jewel b. 1935, twins Donald & Bernard; W. Fulton St)"]},
kateB:{name:"Kate (Gottdank) Bierlein",conf:"verified",years:"20th c.",place:"Chicago, IL",rel:"Daughter of Bernhard & Bertha",facts:{Husband:"Ken Bierlein",Children:"Bernadine · Allen"},story:["The second of Bernhard and Bertha's surviving daughters, between Ruth and Mildred. Their father died in 1917, when the girls were small, so Kate grew up in Bertha's fifty-year widowhood on Chicago's West Side. She married Ken Bierlein and had Bernadine and Allen, and the line carries on under that name."],src:["Family document, Generation 4"]},
twinsHF:{name:"Helen & Florence Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"died young",place:"Chicago, IL",rel:"Twin daughters of Bernhard & Bertha",facts:{Born:"May 24, 1913",Died:"Florence on Sept 16, Helen on Sept 17, 1913",Rest:"Jewish Waldheim Cemetery, Forest Park, outside Chicago"},story:["Bernhard and Bertha's twins. They were born on the same day in May 1913 and died that September, a day apart, at three and a half months old. They're buried at Jewish Waldheim, in Forest Park outside Chicago."],src:["Family document, Generation 3","FindAGrave (Helen & Florence Gottdank, Waldheim Cemetery)"]},
mildredH:{name:"Mildred (Gottdank) Harris",conf:"verified",years:"~1912 – 2006",place:"Wilmette, IL",rel:"Daughter of Bernhard & Bertha",facts:{Married:"Dr. Harold M. Harris, D.D.S.",Sons:"Bruce (Karen), Irvine CA · Irwin F. (June)",Lived:"Wilmette, IL",Died:"2006, aged 94"},story:["The youngest of the Chicago daughters, and the longest-lived. She married Dr. Harold Harris, a dentist, raised sons Bruce and Irwin, and settled in Wilmette on Chicago's North Shore. She died in 2006, at ninety-four, the last of Bernhard and Bertha's children."],src:["Family document","Chicago Tribune / Legacy.com, Mar 2006"]},
pauline:{name:"Pauline (Gottdank) Ascher",conf:"verified",years:"19th–20th c.",place:"Chicago, IL",rel:"Charles's sister · Generation 2",facts:{Son:"Kermit Green"},story:["One of Gittel's two daughters who left Galicia for Chicago, sister to Charles the barber and to Bernhard the shopkeeper. She married an Ascher and her son went by Kermit Green, an Americanized name of the kind that spread through this immigrant generation as they shed the old country. Where exactly she lands in the Cook County records is still a thread to pull."],src:["Family document, Generations 2–3"]},
claraK:{name:"Clara Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"19th–20th c.",place:"Chicago, IL",rel:"Charles's sister · Generation 2",facts:{Married:"into the Korman family",Children:"Lena (Korman) Sandman · Karl Korman",Grandchildren:"Lena's seven children, among them Albert Sandman (1925-2019)"},story:["The other Chicago sister. She married a Korman. Her daughter Lena married Jacob Sandman and raised seven children in Chicago, among them Albert Sandman. Her son was Karl Korman."],src:["Family document, Generations 2-4","Albert Sandman obituary (Lena Korman & Jacob Sandman)"]},
yisroel:{name:"Israel ('Yisroel') Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1909 – 1985",place:"Isterik, Galicia → USSR → Leipheim DP camp → New York",rel:"Holocaust survivor · of the Isterik / Vaytman-Gottdank line",facts:{Origin:"Isterik (Ustrzyki Dolne), Galicia, son of Abraham Weitman & Miriam Gottdank",Survived:"Survived the war in the Soviet Union, then Kyrgyzstan, then enlisted in the army",FirstWife:"Rukhl (née Kalb), born 1909 in Isterik, a tailor in Kraków; married 1933; she and their son Avrom were murdered",SecondWife:"Pnina, an Auschwitz and Ravensbrück survivor picked out of a selection line by Mengele; Miriam's mother (d. 1971)",ThirdWife:"later Shoshana (née Gomerov), a Lithuanian survivor who wrote her own memoir, 'An Uprooted Tree'",Daughter:"Miriam, born 1946 in Günzburg",Route:"Leipheim → Montreal (1948) → Crown Heights, Brooklyn (~1958) → d. New York 1985",Memoir:"Wrote a Yiddish memoir in 1984, the year before he died"},story:["Israel was born in Isterik in 1909. When the Germans came he fled east, into the Soviet Union, and that's how he lived.","His first wife came from his own town. Rukhl Kalb, born the same year as him, ran the book table at Isterik's literary club, and she was the one who put European writing in his hands. She moved to Kraków and worked as a tailor; they married in 1933 and had a son, Avrom. The last trace of her is a Nazi work card from February 1940. She and Avrom were murdered. She was thirty-one.","He started again. After the war he married Pnina, who had lived through Auschwitz, where Mengele picked her out of a line, and then Ravensbrück. He took work as a guard at the Leipheim displaced-persons camp, and their daughter Miriam was born in 1946. They reached Montreal in 1948 and later Brooklyn. The year before he died, Israel wrote his life down in Yiddish, and Miriam, who became a Yiddish scholar, kept it and translated it. One piece she wrote was about Rukhl, the wife he lost, built around four surviving photographs."],gap:"Family memory had two things wrong: he was remembered as Charles's brother (he belongs to the Isterik / Vaytman-Gottdank line instead), and the camp was Leipheim, not Bergen-Belsen. The one thread still on a single source is the match between the death-index 'Israel Gottdank 1909–1985' and the Geni Isterik profile.",src:["Lilith Magazine, 'Four Photographs of Rukhl'","Moment magazine memoir (Mengele tractor factory)","An Uprooted Tree (USHMM, Shoshana Gomerov Gottdank)","Yiddish Book Center / Wexler oral history","SSDI (Israel Gottdank, 1909-1985, NY)"]},
miriamDC:{name:"Miriam Gottdank Isaacs",conf:"verified",years:"b. 1946, living",place:"Günzburg, Germany → Montreal → United States",rel:"Israel's daughter · Yiddish scholar",facts:{Born:"1946 in Günzburg, Germany, Mengele's hometown, while her parents were at the Leipheim DP camp",Education:"PhD, Cornell; taught Yiddish at the University of Maryland for sixteen years",Work:"Yiddish scholar and educator",Translated:"her father's 1984 memoir and Shoshana Gomerov's 'An Uprooted Tree'",Drew:"a portrait of her grandmother 'Maryem Gottdank, midwife of Isterik' from family memory"},story:["Miriam was born in 1946 in Günzburg, the same town Josef Mengele came from, the man who had picked her mother out of a line at Auschwitz two years before. Her parents were at the Leipheim displaced-persons camp; she came to Montreal as a toddler in 1948.","She made a life out of the language her parents carried out with them. She earned a doctorate at Cornell and taught Yiddish at the University of Maryland for sixteen years, and she became the family's bridge to the European story. She translated her father's memoir and another survivor's, drew her murdered grandmother the midwife from the way the family remembered her, and wrote about the women her father lost. The old note that 'Miriam lives in Washington DC' was a mix-up; this is who that Miriam is."],src:["Moment magazine memoir (Mengele tractor factory)","Lilith Magazine, 'Four Photographs of Rukhl'","Yiddish Book Center / Wexler oral history","Jewish Women's Archive, Maryem Gottdank, midwife of Isterik","USHMM, Voices on Antisemitism"]},
unknownB:{name:"The Unknown Brother",conf:"likely",years:"19th–20th c.",place:"New York, Manhattan",rel:"Charles's brother · name forgotten",facts:{Clue:"'Involved with the artist community in Manhattan', the document",Hypothesis:"The unplaced NY Gottdanks (Abraham, Arnold, Samuel...) may be his family"},story:["A sixth sibling, name forgotten, who lived in New York and ran with the artist crowd in Manhattan. A Galician immigrant moving through the Greenwich Village art world in the early 1900s is a life worth recovering, if it can be.","He's also the best explanation for the unplaced New York Gottdanks, the Abraham, Arnold, Harry, and Samuel-and-Anna households that had to come from somebody."],gap:"Name unknown. The 1910–1940 censuses for NY Gottdank households would likely surface him.",src:["Family document, Generation 2"]},
abrahamW:{name:"Abraham Weitman Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"19th c.",place:"Isterik (Ustrzyki Dolne), Galicia",rel:"Married into the name · father of Israel the survivor",facts:{Original:"Born a Vaytman/Weitman",Wife:"Miriam GOTTDANK, the name came from her",Siblings:"David, Jacob & Heynekh Vaytman; Jenny Weitman, a 'Weitmann' family appears in the Isterik martyr list"},story:["This Isterik family carried the name the same way. Abraham was born a Vaytman, and Gottdank came to him through his wife Miriam, exactly as it had for Kalman and Gittel. Their son was Israel, the survivor.","Whether Miriam Gottdank was Gittel's daughter or her kin is the open link between this family and Gittel's line. Same name, same corner of Galicia, same custom. It's begging to be proven."],gap:"Miriam's parents, the missing link to Gittel's family, are not in any indexed record yet.",src:["Geni (documented by Miriam Gottdank Isaacs)","Sefer Yizkor: Linsk, Istrik, Beligrod, Litovisk (Weitmann martyrs)"]},
miriam:{name:"Miriam Gottdank (of Isterik)",conf:"verified",years:"19th c.",place:"Isterik (Ustrzyki Dolne), Galicia",rel:"The Gottdank-born wife of Abraham Vaytman",facts:{Sons:"Israel · Joseph · Rony · Calmen · Moyshe Aaron",Pattern:"Her husband took her name, like Coleman took Gittel's"},story:["Matriarch of the Isterik line, and the one born a Gottdank. She was the town's midwife; her granddaughter remembered her exactly that way, as 'Maryem Gottdank, midwife of Isterik.'","In the autumn of 1942 the Germans emptied Isterik of its Jews. They were marched to the Zasław camp near Sanok and put on trains to the Bełżec death camp, and Maryem was among them. Her name is in the town's memorial book, written as Miriam Weitmann, the married name she carried. If she was Gittel's daughter or kin, the two families are one tree, and Israel the survivor is the proof in human form."],src:["Geni family tree","Family document (naming parallel)","Sefer Yizkor: Linsk, Istrik (Miriam Weitmann, martyr list)","Virtual Shtetl (POLIN), Ustrzyki Dolne","Bełżec deportation list (Sanok district, Sept 1942)"]},
israel:{name:"Israel Gottdank, the survivor",conf:"verified",years:"1909 – 1985",place:"Isterik → USSR → Leipheim → New York",rel:"Son of Abraham & Miriam · the same man the family called 'Yisroel'",facts:{Same:"He is the family's 'Yisroel', one man, two memories now joined (full story in his record)",Born:"August 28, 1909",Died:"New York, 1985",Daughter:"Miriam Gottdank Isaacs (b. 1946)"},story:["The 'Israel of Kraków' and the 'Yisroel' the family remembered are the same man: Israel Gottdank of Isterik, who survived the war in the Soviet Union and rebuilt a family at the Leipheim DP camp.","He was a son of Abraham Weitman and Miriam Gottdank of Isterik. That's the link that ties this branch to the survivor, and it shows the 'Kraków' label was really Isterik all along."],src:["Moment magazine memoir","Yiddish Book Center oral history","Geni (Isterik / Vaytman-Gottdank)","SSDI (1909–1985, NY)"]},
joseph_g:{name:"Joseph · Rony · Calmen · Moyshe Aaron",conf:"likely",years:"early 20th c.",place:"Isterik (Ustrzyki Dolne), Galicia",rel:"Israel's siblings · murdered in the Shoah",facts:{Joseph:"'Yosl', a shoemaker who stayed in Isterik with his wife and small son; all murdered",Martyrs:"The Isterik Yizkor book names WEITMANN Yakov Yentche and Miriam among the town's dead, the family's Weitman name (no 'Gottdank' appears, fitting the matrilineal custom)",Documented:"Their profiles and the one surviving photo were entered by Israel's daughter, Miriam Gottdank Isaacs"},story:["Israel's brothers and sisters, who didn't get out. Joseph, 'Yosl,' trained as a shoemaker and stayed in Isterik. One photograph survives of him with his wife and their small son at the edges of the frame. They were murdered in 1942, when the town's Jews were taken to the Zasław camp and on to Bełżec.","Their name is in print. The 1965 Yizkor book for Linsk, Istrik, and the villages around them lists Yakov Yentche Weitmann and Miriam Weitmann among the murdered of Ustrzyki Dolne. They show up as Weitman, not Gottdank; the wife's name only attached at marriage."],src:["Sefer Yizkor: Linsk, Istrik, Beligrod, Litovisk (Tel Aviv, 1965), martyr list, p. 478","Geni (Isterik / Vaytman-Gottdank, documented by Miriam Isaacs)","Zasław transit camp record","Bełżec deportation list (Sanok district, Sept 1942)"]},
davidO:{name:"David Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"~1880 – 1922",place:"London → Ottawa",rel:"Immigrant patriarch, Ottawa line",facts:{Married:"Rachel Leah Cohen, London",Emigrated:"~1905–1910",Died:"Aug 31, 1922, tuberculosis",Buried:"Jewish Memorial Gardens, Ottawa"},story:["He married Rachel in London and brought her to Ottawa around 1905, where the 1911 census found them in Victoria Ward with their children. He raised five of them and died of tuberculosis in 1922, in his early forties."],src:["FindAGrave 256993440, citing Ottawa Jewish Archives","1911 Census of Canada (Victoria Ward, Ottawa)","Jewish Memorial Gardens, Ottawa"]},
rachelO:{name:"Rachel Leah Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"d. 1938",place:"London → Ottawa",rel:"Immigrant matriarch, Ottawa line",facts:{Maiden:"Cohen, confirmed on her Ottawa gravestone (the Geni 'Nitupski' is wrong)",Died:"March 20, 1938",Widowed:"1922, with five children"},story:["Rachel was born in the Russian Empire around 1881 and married David in London, so London was the waypoint, not home. After he died in 1922 she raised Sarah, Esther, Jeanne, Arthur, and Syd on her own for sixteen years. She started all three daughters on music early, Sarah at the piano, Esther on cello, Jeanne on violin, and that decision put two of them on the American vaudeville circuit."],src:["FindAGrave 256993443","Geni (Rachel Gottdank profile)","1911 Census of Canada (Rachel born about 1881, Russia)"]},
estherO:{name:"Esther Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1904 – 1988",place:"Ottawa → vaudeville America",rel:"Daughter of David & Rachel · the touring cellist",facts:{Start:"Played silent-movie accompaniment, Allen's Danforth Theatre, Toronto",Stage:"'The Roumanian Serenaders' → 'The Slaves of Melody' (from ~1926)",StageName:"Performed as Esther GORDON",Married:"David Mirsky in NY, Jan 19 1932, kept secret to protect her Canadian tax-department job; nephew of Rev. Jacob Mirsky"},story:["Esther learned cello because her widowed mother insisted on it. She started in the orchestra pit at Allen's Danforth Theatre in Toronto, playing live to silent movies, then around 1926 joined a touring Chicago vaudeville troupe, the Roumanian Serenaders, later the Slaves of Melody, and rode the American circuit for five years.","On the road she and her sister went by a stage name, and it turns up in the papers: a 1927 Indiana bill lists 'the Gordon sisters, who play the violin and cello.' The Gottdank girls had become the Gordons. She came home to Ottawa, married David Mirsky in New York in 1932, and kept the wedding quiet to protect her job at the tax department. She played to the end of her life and was a life member of the city's musicians' union; she died in 1988. Her daughter Deborah later gave the family's papers, vaudeville schedules and all, to the Ottawa Jewish Archives, which is why so much of this branch survives."],src:["Geni / Ottawa Jewish Archives (Gottdank family fonds)","South Bend News-Times, Oct 23 1927 (the Gordon sisters)","Jewish Memorial Gardens, Ottawa (Esther Mirsky)"]},
jeanneO:{name:"Jeanne Gottdank Lieff",conf:"verified",years:"1906 – 2003",place:"Ottawa",rel:"Daughter of David & Rachel · violinist",facts:{Toured:"Joined the Serenaders with Esther ~1926; left after two years",StageName:"Performed as a 'Gordon' sister",Married:"Louis Lieff, brother of Justice Abraham H. Lieff (1903–2007)",Lived:"96 years"},story:["The violinist of the three sisters, in the Ottawa Philharmonic by the time she was thirteen. She toured vaudeville with Esther under the Gordon name for two years, then came home and married Louis Lieff, whose brother Abraham became the first Jewish justice of Ontario's Supreme Court. She kept playing in Ottawa's orchestras almost to her 97th birthday, in 2003."],src:["Geni / Ottawa Jewish Archives","Jewish Memorial Gardens, Ottawa (Jeanne Lieff)","Bill Gladstone, Justice Abraham Lieff at 100"]},
sasO:{name:"Sarah & Syd Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"early 1900s",place:"Ottawa",rel:"Children of David & Rachel",facts:{Sarah:"The pianist (1900–1958), married Harry Torontow, Nov 1925; sons David & Abraham Torontow",Syd:"Took the surname GORDON, the name his sisters toured under"},story:["Sarah, the eldest, was the pianist; she married Harry Torontow of Ottawa's well-known Torontow family in 1925 and had two sons, David and Abraham. She lived from 1900 to 1958. Their brother Syd took the surname Gordon, the same name his sisters performed under, which is why the Sidney Gottdank later found in Ridgecrest, California is probably a different man."],src:["Geni / Ottawa Jewish Archives","Torontow family fonds (CJHN)"]},
arthur:{name:"Arthur J. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1910 – 1983",place:"Ottawa, ON",rel:"Son of David & Rachel · father of the Canadian line",facts:{Born:"1910, Ottawa (after the family's ~1905–10 arrival)",Died:"1983, per his public FamilySearch profile (LBJ2-M7K)",Wife:"Violet Kathleen (~1925–2014)",Children:"Robert 'Bob' · David 'Lee' · Michael 'Kim' · Tina Lou"},story:["The one boy in that musical Ottawa house, and the one who carried the name on. While his sisters toured, Arthur stayed home, married Violet Kathleen, and raised four children. Every Gottdank in Canada today comes through them.","For a long time he was just a first name on the chart. Now he's bracketed by dates, 1910 to 1983. He was buried at Capital Memorial Gardens, a secular cemetery, not with his parents in the Jewish ground on Bank Street."],src:["Violet Gottdank obituary, Ottawa Citizen, Apr 30 2014","FamilySearch profile LBJ2-M7K (Arthur J Gottdank, 1910-1983)","Capital Memorial Gardens, Ottawa (plot 330C-1)"]},
violet:{name:"Violet Kathleen Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"~1925 – 2014",place:"Ottawa, ON",rel:"Wife of Arthur · matriarch of the Canadian line",facts:{Maiden:"née Fisher, parents Thomas Fisher & Maria Durocher",Died:"April 28, 2014, Carleton Lodge, in her 89th year",Children:"Bob (Rita) · Lee (Joyce) · Kim (Janet) · the late Tina Lou (Rick)",Grandchildren:"Steven (Celina) · Danny (Celia) · Kayla (Thomas) · Lauren · Nathan",Also:"5 great-grandchildren; sisters Gladys & the late Lena",Rest:"Capital Funeral Home & Cemetery, Prince of Wales Dr"},story:["The hinge of the Canadian branch. Born Violet Fisher in 1925, she married Arthur, and through them two whole generations come into view, four children and five grandchildren, tying the modern Canadian Gottdanks back to the immigrant line. She died in 2014, in her 89th year; her headstone carries the crest of the IODE, the Imperial Order Daughters of the Empire.","Two more Gottdank women belong here too: Edith and Barbara, daughters-in-law who signed her guestbook 'in remembrance of our Mother-in-Law.'"],src:["Ottawa Citizen obituary, Apr 30 2014 (full text via Legacy.com)","Ancestry (Violet Fisher, born Aug 25 1925)"]},
bobG:{name:"Robert 'Bob' Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Thornhill, ON",rel:"Son of Arthur & Violet",facts:{Wife:"Rita (attended Perth & District Collegiate)",Confirmed:"Named 'Bob Gottdank of Thornhill' in sister Tina's 1987 death notice"},story:["The eldest son. When his sister Tina died in 1987, the Ottawa Citizen notice named him plainly, 'Bob Gottdank of Thornhill,' which settles that the Robert Gottdank up in that town north of Toronto is Arthur and Violet's boy. His wife Rita went to Perth and District Collegiate, out in the Lanark County town west of Ottawa, so the marriage reaches back into the family's own part of eastern Ontario. Edith Gottdank, a daughter-in-law of Arthur and Violet, lives in the same Thornhill area."],src:["Violet Gottdank obituary","Ottawa Citizen, Tina Gottdank-Normoyle death notice, 1987 ('Bob Gottdank of Thornhill', brother)","LocateFamily (Thornhill records)"]},
davidGreely:{name:"David 'Lee' Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Greely, ON (Ottawa)",rel:"Son of Arthur & Violet",facts:{Named:"After his grandfather, the immigrant David",Wife:"Joyce",Location:"Greely, ten miles from his grandfather's grave"},story:["Violet's son David 'Lee,' with Joyce, lives in Greely, an Ottawa suburb ten miles from Jewish Memorial Gardens, where the first David Gottdank was buried in 1922. A grandson carrying his grandfather's name, just the way Jewish naming tradition would predict."],src:["Violet Gottdank obituary (named son)","LocateFamily (Greely, ON)"]},
kimG:{name:"Michael 'Kim' Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Kemptville / Nepean, ON",rel:"Son of Arthur & Violet · entrepreneur",facts:{Wife:"Janet",Companies:"COM/MIT Financial · COM/MIT Hitech · Clean.Net Inc.",Area:"Kemptville, Lanark, Nepean, greater Ottawa"},story:["Violet's son Michael 'Kim,' with Janet. The 'M. Kim Gottdank' and 'Michael K. Gottdank' who own three companies out in the Ottawa countryside are the same man, the immigrants' grandson turned small-business owner."],src:["Violet Gottdank obituary (named son)","CompaniesOfCanada / OpenCorporates: M. Kim Gottdank, director, COM/MIT Hitech Services Inc., Kemptville ON"]},
tinaG:{name:"Tina Louise Gottdank-Normoyle",conf:"verified",years:"~1959 – 1987",place:"Ontario",rel:"Daughter of Arthur & Violet",facts:{Died:"Friday, January 30, 1987, aged 27",Husband:"Richard 'Rick' Normoyle",Son:"Nathan",Survivors:"Mother Violet (Fisher) Gottdank; brother Bob of Thornhill"},story:["Arthur and Violet's daughter, lost young. She died on a Friday, January 30, 1987, at twenty-seven, leaving her husband Richard Normoyle and their son Nathan. The Ottawa Citizen notice named her as the daughter of Violet Fisher Gottdank and the late Arthur, with Bob of Thornhill her brother.","Her boy Nathan, one of the grandchildren listed in Violet's obituary years later, carries the line on."],src:["Ottawa Citizen death notice, Jan 31 1987 (Tina Louise Gottdank-Normoyle, age 27; wife of Richard Normoyle; mother of Nathan; daughter of Violet & the late Arthur)"]},
danny:{name:"Danny Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Toronto, ON",rel:"Grandson of Arthur & Violet",facts:{Wife:"Celia",Work:"Talent Acquisition Manager, Technology, Rogers Communications",Education:"York University",Lineage:"Great-great-grandson of David & Rachel"},story:["Danny runs technology recruiting at Rogers in Toronto, the hire-the-hirers job, pulling in network operations people, cloud engineers, cybersecurity advisors for the country's biggest telecom. He's Arthur's grandson and a great-great-grandson of the London couple who landed in Ottawa around 1905.","Four generations from the boat to the recruiter's desk, and the name made the whole trip."],src:["Violet Gottdank obituary (named grandson)","Danny Gottdank LinkedIn (Talent Acquisition Manager, Technology, Rogers Communications)","LocateFamily"]},
celia:{name:"Celia Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living/recent",place:"Markham / Bradford, ON",rel:"Wife of Danny",facts:{Named:"'Danny (Celia)' in Violet's obituary",Household:"Breeze Drive, same address & phone as Danny"},story:["Danny's wife, written as 'Danny (Celia)' in Violet's 2014 obituary, which is how the Ottawa branch named its grandchildren's spouses. They share a household on Breeze Drive, north of Toronto. She marries into a line that runs back through Arthur in Ottawa to the couple who crossed from London around 1905."],src:["Violet Gottdank obituary","LocateFamily (shared household)"]},
steven:{name:"Steven Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Toronto, ON",rel:"Grandson of Arthur & Violet",facts:{Wife:"Celina",Listed:"South Kingsway, Toronto"},story:["Violet's grandson, named 'Steven (Celina)' in her obituary, listed on South Kingsway in west-end Toronto. He's one of the handful of Arthur and Violet's grandchildren, the generation that moved the Canadian line off the Ottawa ground their great-grandparents settled and into the bigger city. The whole Toronto cluster in this tree traces back to that one Ottawa couple."],src:["Violet Gottdank obituary (named grandson)","LocateFamily (Toronto)"]},
grandkidsCA:{name:"Kayla · Lauren · Nathan",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Ontario",rel:"Grandchildren of Arthur & Violet",facts:{Kayla:"married Thomas",Plus:"Five great-grandchildren by 2014"},story:["The rest of Violet's grandchildren. By 2014 the Canadian line had reached five great-grandchildren, a sixth living generation from David and Rachel's 1905 crossing."],src:["Violet Gottdank obituary"]},
torontoMisc:{name:"Edith & Barbara Gottdank",conf:"likely",years:"living/recent",place:"Thornhill, ON & Canton, MA",rel:"Daughters-in-law of Arthur & Violet (self-identified)",facts:{Evidence:"Signed Violet's guestbook: 'In remembrance of our Mother-in-Law'",Edith:"Thornhill / North York directory records",Barbara:"Canton, MA record"},story:["Two more living Gottdank women, Edith and Barbara, daughters-in-law of Arthur and Violet. Which sons they married is the open detail, though Edith's Thornhill address matches Robert's town."],gap:"Exact pairing to Violet's sons unstated.",src:["Violet obituary guestbook (self-identified)","LocateFamily records"]},
nyimm:{name:"Unplaced New York Gottdanks",conf:"verified",years:"b. 1884 – 1902",place:"Brooklyn · Bronx · Manhattan",rel:"Likely the Unknown Brother's family, or close kin",facts:{Members:"Abraham (1884–1975, Brooklyn) · Samuel ⚭ Anna (1887–1980) → Esther Brody · Sophie (1889–1984) · Annie (1890–1986) · Arnold (1895–1975, Manhattan) · Harry (1895–1975)",Households:"Two married Gottdank couples surface in the census: Benjamin ⚭ Sophie in the Bronx (→ Ruth, Mildred) and Louis ⚭ May (née Stillman) in Brooklyn (→ Mildred, Claire), likely the unknown brother's sons",Hypothesis:"The 'unknown brother' of Manhattan is the best candidate for their father"},story:["These New Yorkers are the leftover, and the forgotten sixth sibling, the one in the Manhattan art world, is the likeliest father or uncle. The dates settle into one set: Abraham, born 1884, died in Brooklyn at ninety; Sophie, 1889, out in Rockaway Park; Arnold, 1895, in Manhattan to the end. Two of them, Harry and Annie, turn up dying in Los Angeles, so part of this New York set went west.","The census is starting to sort them into households: a Benjamin Gottdank and family in the Bronx, a Louis Gottdank and family in Brooklyn, two married Gottdank men of the right age who are most likely the unknown brother's sons. The brother himself stays just out of reach."],src:["SSDI","1920-1950 US Census (Benjamin/Bronx, Louis/Brooklyn households)","AncientFaces (Gottdank death records)","Family document (unknown brother)"]},
nygen:{name:"NY-born, still unplaced",conf:"verified",years:"b. 1908 – 1924",place:"New York City",rel:"The rest of the American-born band",facts:{Members:"Gladys (1908) · Rosa (1910) · David (1911) · Mildred (1916) · Christine (1918) · Terry (1918) · Beatrice (1919) · Lawrence (1919) · Seymour (1920) · Leon (1922, buried at LA's Hillside) · Barbara (1924)",Placed:"Jerome=Jerry ✓ · Milton ✓ · Molly ✓ · Irving (El Cajon) likely Chicago-or-NY kin"},story:["Jerry and Milton stepped out of this anonymous band into the documented family. The rest are still waiting. Most are probably children of the unknown brother, or New York cousins of Charles, first cousins of Milton's generation who scattered later to Florida and California."],src:["Social Security Death Index","LA Times (Leon, Hillside Mortuary)"]},
lawrence:{name:"Lawrence Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1919 – 1998",place:"NY → Pompano Beach, FL",rel:"Plainview patriarch (inferred)",facts:{Born:"May 23, 1919",Died:"Oct 27, 1998"},story:["Born the same year as Beatrice and died in the Florida retirement belt. He's the natural father for the Plainview household, though the marriage is an inference, not a record."],gap:"Marriage to Beatrice inferred from matching years + Long Island geography.",src:["SSDI"]},
beatrice:{name:"Beatrice Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1919 – 2009",place:"Plainview, NY & Margate, FL",rel:"Plainview matriarch",facts:{Born:"July 4, 1919",Died:"Feb 8, 2009, aged 89"},story:["A Fourth-of-July baby who lived to eighty-nine and wintered in Margate, Florida. Her Plainview address is one street over from the household of Joseph, Ellen, Heather, and Tracy."],src:["SSDI","LocateFamily (Plainview & Margate)"]},
josephP:{name:"Joseph D. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Plainview, NY",rel:"Son of Lawrence & Beatrice (inferred)",facts:{Household:"29 Alma Lane, Plainview, with Ellen N., Heather A., Tracy S.",Phone:"One household line shared by all four (516) 639-4186"},story:["Head of the household at 29 Alma Lane in Plainview, the postwar Long Island suburb where a lot of New York Jewish families landed when they left the city. He's there with Ellen and their daughters Heather and Tracy, all four on the same phone line, the kind of detail that ties a family together in the public record even when nothing else does.","Beatrice's old address sat a street over, and the timing fits, so the likeliest read is that Joseph is Lawrence and Beatrice's son. No document spells the parentage out, so that part stays a careful guess."],gap:"Parentage inferred; no document names it.",src:["ClustrMaps / LocateFamily (29 Alma Lane: Joseph D., Ellen N., Heather A., Tracy S. Gottdank, shared phone)"]},
ellenP:{name:"Ellen Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Plainview, NY",rel:"Wife of Joseph",facts:{Household:"Alma Lane, Plainview"},story:["Ellen at 29 Alma Lane, the name beside Joseph's across two decades of Plainview records. Plainview was potato and pickle farmland until the early fifties, when builders threw up split-levels almost overnight and the new houses filled with young families leaving Brooklyn and Queens for a yard and a good school district. That is the world the Alma Lane household sits in, four names on one phone line, raising Heather and Tracy."],src:["LocateFamily","ClustrMaps (29 Alma Lane household)"]},
heather:{name:"Heather Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Plainview, NY",rel:"Daughter of Joseph & Ellen",facts:{Household:"Alma Lane, Plainview"},story:["One of the two daughters raised at 29 Alma Lane in Plainview, the postwar Long Island suburb of split-levels and good schools that drew young Jewish families out of the city. She and Tracy are the next generation of the household, listed on the same line as their parents."],src:["LocateFamily (shared household)"]},
tracy:{name:"Tracy Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Plainview / Franklin Sq, NY",rel:"Daughter of Joseph & Ellen",facts:{Household:"Alma Lane; later Franklin Square"},story:["The other daughter raised at 29 Alma Lane, and the one the record follows out the door: a later listing of her own in Franklin Square, a few towns west toward the Queens line. That short hop is the next Long Island generation setting out on its own, staying close to where it grew up."],src:["LocateFamily (shared household + Franklin Sq)"]},
roseEC:{name:"Rose (Tuchfeld) Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1902 – 1995",place:"Los Angeles → San Diego, CA",rel:"The Los Angeles matriarch",facts:{Born:"Dec 26, 1902, parents Morris Tuchfeld & Dora Schloss",Husband:"Harry Gottdank",Children:"Irving · Sydney (and Paul)",Died:"July 9, 1995, near San Diego"},story:["The mother of the California Gottdanks. Rose was born a Tuchfeld, married Harry Gottdank, and raised the family in Los Angeles; the 1940 and 1950 censuses put Harry and Rose there with their sons Irving and Sydney. She died near San Diego in 1995, at ninety-two."],src:["1940 & 1950 US Census, Los Angeles","SSDI","Rose Gottdank death record, San Diego 1995"]},
irving:{name:"Irving E. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1925 – 2014",place:"Los Angeles → El Cajon, CA",rel:"Son of Harry & Rose · Milton's generation",facts:{Born:"September 11, 1925, to Harry & Rose (Tuchfeld) Gottdank, Los Angeles",Brother:"Sydney Gottdank",Died:"January 22, 2014, El Cajon",Address:"Alderson Street, El Cajon"},story:["Born in Los Angeles in 1925 to Harry and Rose Gottdank, Irving settled down the coast in El Cajon. He was four years younger than Milton and of the same American-born generation, a likely cousin, living out his years twenty minutes from Dale's San Diego without either side necessarily knowing.","His brother Sydney is very probably the Sidney Gottdank later found up in Ridgecrest."],src:["1940 & 1950 US Census, Los Angeles","Legacy.com obituary, Jan 22 2014"]},
sidney:{name:"Sidney Gottdank",conf:"likely",years:"living/recent",place:"Los Angeles → Ridgecrest, CA",rel:"Likely Harry & Rose's son · Irving's brother",facts:{Origin:"Very likely the 'Sydney' the Los Angeles census lists as Harry & Rose Gottdank's son, Irving's brother",Household:"Farragut Street, Ridgecrest, with Linda L.",Town:"Ridgecrest = the China Lake naval weapons base"},story:["Sidney and Linda shared a household in Ridgecrest, the desert town built around the China Lake weapons base, which hints at defense work. He's very likely the Sydney the Los Angeles census names as Harry and Rose's son, which would make him Irving's brother and tie Ridgecrest to the California family."],gap:"The Ridgecrest Sidney = LA Sydney match is strong (same name, same state, right family), but not pinned by a single record.",src:["1940 & 1950 US Census, Los Angeles (Harry & Rose → Sydney)","LocateFamily (Ridgecrest household)"]},
linda:{name:"Linda L. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living/recent",place:"Ridgecrest, CA",rel:"Wife of Sidney",facts:{Household:"Same Farragut St address"},story:["Linda L., listed with Sidney at the Farragut Street household across twenty years of records. Ridgecrest is a company town in the Mojave, built up around the Navy's China Lake weapons station, where most of the working population draws a government or contractor paycheck. That desert posting is about all the public record gives of the two of them, two names on one address far out in the California high desert."],src:["LocateFamily"]},
alex:{name:"Alex Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"San Juan Capistrano, CA",rel:"Author & teacher · OC cluster",facts:{Author:"'Preparing for Christ's New Name' (2004)",Faith:"Bahá'í, from a Jewish/Christian background",Service:"Nat'l Spiritual Assembly, W. Caroline Islands, 1988–2000"},story:["Alex grew up in a Jewish and Christian family and read the Gospel for the first time at sixteen. The questions it raised kept going. A three-year conversation with a Bahá'í friend about the return of Christ turned into his 2004 book, 'Preparing for Christ's New Name.' He spent twelve years on the Bahá'í National Spiritual Assembly of the Western Caroline Islands and taught at Yap High School in Micronesia, and he now teaches seventh-grade world history in San Juan Capistrano."],src:["Preparing for Christ's New Name (Naturegraph, 2004)","Alex Gottdank, BahaiTeachings.org author page"]},
marilyn:{name:"Marilyn B. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living/recent",place:"San Clemente / Vista, CA",rel:"OC cluster, likely Alex's household",facts:{Towns:"San Clemente & Vista, minutes from San Juan Capistrano"},story:["Marilyn lives in San Clemente, ten minutes from Alex's San Juan Capistrano, and Adam's household record names her alongside Alex and him. That ties the three south Orange County Gottdanks into one family; her exact place in it isn't written down."],gap:"Link to Alex inferred from tight geography only.",src:["LocateFamily (San Clemente/Vista)","ThatsThem (Adam's household lists Marilyn)"]},
adam:{name:"Adam S.U. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Laguna Niguel, CA",rel:"OC cluster",facts:{Role:"Associate Dean & Director of Disability Support Services, North Orange County Community College District",Wrote:"co-author, 'Transition, A Conversation with Parents'",Home:"Laguna Niguel"},story:["Adam runs disability support services for the North Orange County Community College District, and co-wrote a guide for parents on a young person's transition to adult life. He lives in Laguna Niguel, and his household record lists Alex and Marilyn alongside him, which ties the three south Orange County Gottdanks into one family, even if the record doesn't spell out who is whose parent."],gap:"Cluster relationships inferred from geography.",src:["ThatsThem (Adam Gottdank household)","openpayrolls / LinkedIn"]},
michaelNJ:{name:"Michael D. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"East Brunswick, NJ",rel:"Unplaced, New York roots",facts:{Career:"Managing Director, Equitas Advisors / Equitas Brokerage Group, East Brunswick NJ",Earlier:"Led carrier and solution sales across Western Europe for IDT",Education:"MBA, Tel Aviv University"},story:["Michael runs an insurance brokerage shop in East Brunswick, a managing director at Equitas, where he helps property-and-casualty agents add life, health, and financial planning to what they sell. Before that he was overseas for the telecom IDT, building and running its carrier-sales team across Western Europe, and he picked up his MBA at Tel Aviv University along the way.","He's a born New Yorker who landed in central New Jersey, and we can't yet pin his branch to the rest of the tree. The one New Jersey death record in the name, a Rosa Gottdank who lived from 1910 to 1987, might be his grandmother. That thread is still loose."],gap:"Unplaced; the Rosa Gottdank (NJ, 1910-1987) link is a guess, not a record.",src:["ZoomInfo / ContactOut (Michael D. Gottdank, Managing Director, Equitas Advisors, East Brunswick NJ; IDT Western Europe; Tel Aviv University MBA)","LocateFamily (East Brunswick)"]},
mariza:{name:"Mariza & Fernando Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living/recent",place:"São Paulo & Santos, Brazil",rel:"The Brazilian branch",facts:{Mariza:"Santos → São Paulo; founded the language school 'Dank Idiomas' in 2010",Fernando:"Fernando Adrian Gottdank, a São Paulo graphic designer who made aliyah in 2019; survived the Oct 7, 2023 attack at the Universo Paralello rave in Israel",Roots:"Her father was Ihdy Herch Alfabet, of a family that fled the Nazis to Brazil; the Gottdank name reaches her through her mother"},story:["The name reached South America. Mariza grew up poor in the port city of Santos; her father, Ihdy Herch Alfabet, died when she was thirteen, and an uncle paid for the English course that changed everything. She ran the elevator at the local newspaper, started teaching English on the side in 1993, moved to São Paulo, and in 2010 opened her own language school, Dank Idiomas, named off the back half of the family name.","Her father's people were Alfabet, refugees who fled the Nazis to Brazil, so the Gottdank name reaches her through her mother. Fernando Gottdank is the other Brazilian who carries it: a São Paulo graphic designer who made aliyah in 2019. He was at the Universo Paralello rave in the Israeli south on October 7, 2023, and got out alive, sheltering in a bunker and then driving clear of the festival the attack overran."],gap:"Which Gottdank emigrated to Brazil, and through which parent, is still open; Santos port records would resolve it.",src:["Dank Idiomas (Mariza Gottdank profile & interview)","Metrópoles, Oct 2023 (Fernando, Universo Paralello)","Behance (Fernando Gottdank portfolio)"]},
};
